ialist model-so dominant in feminist jurisprudence-to the study of masculinities. She demonstrates how men’s treatment by the law and society in general varies by race, economic position, sexuality, and other factors. She applies these insights to both boys and men, examining how masculinities analysis exposes both privilege and subordination. She examines men’s experienceof fatherhood and sexual abuse, and boys’ experience in the contexts of education and juvenile justice. Ultimately, Dowd calls for a more inclusive feminist theory, which, by acknowledging the study of masculinities, can broaden our understanding of privilege and subordination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aFatherhood. 0aFeminist theory. 0aMasculinity. 0aMenxLegal status, laws, etc. 0aSex and law. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh  aDowd.  aNancy.  aanti-essentialist.  aapply.  adominant.  aexhorts.  afeminist.  agroundbreaking.  ajurisprudenceto.  alegal.  amasculinities.  amodelso.  areaders.  astudy.  atheorist.  athis.  awork.1 aShaw, Ted, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081472005940uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814720059.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814785379423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814785379/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK